trans-unit.source: Creates a custom finite or infinite impulse response filter
trans-unit.target: Creates a custom finite or infinite impulse response filter

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>User-Defined Filter</ui> module to define a custom filter by using a finite impulse response (FIR) filter or an infinite impulse response (IIR) filter with coefficients that you specify.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>User-Defined Filter</ui> module to define a custom filter by using a finite impulse response (FIR) filter or an infinite impulse response (IIR) filter with coefficients that you specify.

trans-unit.source: This module is particularly useful for applying a set of previously derived filter coefficients to your data.
trans-unit.target: This module is particularly useful for applying a set of previously derived filter coefficients to your data.

trans-unit.source: After you have defined a filter that meets your needs, you can apply the filter to data by connecting a dataset and the filter to the <link xlink:href="278e11ec-cb16-49d4-a13c-54b2c9f5ce88" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Apply Filter</link> module.
trans-unit.target: After you have defined a filter that meets your needs, you can apply the filter to data by connecting a dataset and the filter to the <link xlink:href="278e11ec-cb16-49d4-a13c-54b2c9f5ce88" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Apply Filter</link> module.

trans-unit.source: How to Configure a Custom Filter
trans-unit.target: How to Configure a Custom Filter

trans-unit.source: When you define a custom filter, you must first define the filter type, and then provide the coefficients.
trans-unit.target: When you define a custom filter, you must first define the filter type, and then provide the coefficients.

trans-unit.source: The requirements are different depending on whether you choose a FIR filter or an IIR filter.
trans-unit.target: The requirements are different depending on whether you choose a FIR filter or an IIR filter.

trans-unit.source: This topic includes examples of both types.
trans-unit.target: This topic includes examples of both types.

trans-unit.source: When you are deciding which filter type to use, consider the following:
trans-unit.target: When you are deciding which filter type to use, consider the following:

trans-unit.source: For a FIR filter, you specify a vector of feed-forward coefficients.
trans-unit.target: For a FIR filter, you specify a vector of feed-forward coefficients.

trans-unit.source: The length of the vector determines the filter's order.
trans-unit.target: The length of the vector determines the filter's order.

trans-unit.source: A FIR filter is effectively a moving average, so the configuration values apply a moving average to filter a data sequence.
trans-unit.target: A FIR filter is effectively a moving average, so the configuration values apply a moving average to filter a data sequence.

trans-unit.source: For an IIR filter, you apply custom feed-forward and feed-backward coefficients.
trans-unit.target: For an IIR filter, you apply custom feed-forward and feed-backward coefficients.

trans-unit.source: The following examples demonstrate some configuration values.
trans-unit.target: The following examples demonstrate some configuration values.

trans-unit.source: FIR Filter Example: Exponential Weighted Moving Average
trans-unit.target: FIR Filter Example: Exponential Weighted Moving Average

trans-unit.source: For an exponentially weighted moving average, all coefficients are less than one and the sum of all coefficients equals one.
trans-unit.target: For an exponentially weighted moving average, all coefficients are less than one and the sum of all coefficients equals one.

trans-unit.source: Therefore, the variance of the weighted average will always be less than the input values.
trans-unit.target: Therefore, the variance of the weighted average will always be less than the input values.
